<AcademyLayout title="Architecture Differences">
  
  <Breadcrumbs partTitle="PART VII: Architecture" chapterTitle="Architecture Differences" />

  <h1>Architecture Differences</h1>

  <Prerequisites 
    difficulty="Advanced" 
    links={[
      { title: "What We Discovered", url: "/attentionheadgenome/academy/part5-experimental-findings" }
    ]}
  />

  <div class="lead">
    Is the HeadGenome Taxonomy a universal property of Transformers, or is it just an artifact of training on English data? To answer this, we tested four radically different architectures.
  </div>

  <h2>1. Multi-Head Attention vs Grouped-Query Attention</h2>

  <WhyCare>
    Understanding how architectural choices impact the HeadGenome allows us to design better base models from scratch, rather than just optimizing them after training.
  </WhyCare>

  <p>
    We tested models with standard Multi-Head Attention (MHA) like GPT-2, and models with Grouped-Query Attention (GQA) like Llama-3.2-1B and Qwen-1.5B.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>GQA compresses the taxonomy.</strong> Because GQA forces multiple Query heads to share a single Value head, the V/Q Ratio is structurally constrained. Despite this intense bottleneck, the models still successfully carve out the Four Species. The V/Q Spatial Scaling Law survives GQA perfectly.
  </p>

  <h2>2. The Universality Proofs</h2>

  <p>
    To prove that the taxonomy is a fundamental property of the transformer engine and not a side-effect of language, we subjected the models to three stress tests.
  </p>

  <h3>A. The Initialization Null</h3>
  <p>
    We tested an untrained, randomly initialized GPT-2 model. It showed absolutely zero taxonomy and no V/Q scaling law. This proves the structure is learned via gradient descent, not hardcoded into the PyTorch classes.
  </p>

  <h3>B. The Permutation Null</h3>
  <p>
    We fed the models completely shuffled, randomized gibberish. The Induction heads still fired. This proves Induction heads are structural pattern-matchers, not semantic language processors.
  </p>

  <h3>C. The Cross-Domain Proof</h3>
  <p>
    We compared GPT-2 (trained on 2019 English WebText), Qwen (trained on modern Multilingual data), and Llama (trained on Code and Math instructions). Despite existing in entirely different training universes, all three models developed identical head species distributions and identical V/Q scaling slopes.
  </p>
  
  <div class="code-block" style="color: var(--text-2);">
    # Across completely different training datasets:<br>
    Sink Heads:       ~3% to ~5%<br>
    Local Heads:      ~82% to ~85%<br>
    Retrieval Heads:  ~8% to ~10%<br>
    Induction Heads:  ~2% to ~4%
  </div>

  <Misconception>
    <Fragment slot="myth">Bigger models have completely different, more "alien" mechanisms than smaller models.</Fragment>
    <Fragment slot="truth">No. The biological ratios of Sink, Local, and Retrieval heads remain incredibly stable as parameters scale. The "brain" gets bigger, but the cellular anatomy remains the same.</Fragment>
  </Misconception>

  <h2>3. Absolute Embeddings vs RoPE</h2>
  
  <p>
    As discussed in Part I, GPT-2 uses absolute embeddings, while Llama uses Rotary Position Embeddings (RoPE). 
  </p>
  <p>
    Because RoPE calculates relative distance dynamically, Llama models are incredibly resilient to KV Cache eviction (Part VI). When we evict tokens from GPT-2, the absolute position embeddings of the remaining tokens become mathematically corrupted, causing immediate model collapse. 
  </p>

  <CouldBeWrong>
    <p>We claim the Taxonomy is invariant across domains (English vs. Code vs. Math).</p>
    <p><strong>Alternative Explanation:</strong> We only tested standard LLM tasks. If we trained a transformer purely on reinforcement learning states (e.g., AlphaStar or Decision Transformer) or pure Vision (ViT), the Taxonomy might completely change.</p>
    <p><strong>Experiment to verify:</strong> Run the HeadGenome entropy pipeline on a Vision Transformer (ViT) generating image patches to see if Spatial/Local heads emerge instead of Grammar/Local heads.</p>
  </CouldBeWrong>

  <InterviewQuestions title="Research Defense & Discussion">
    <details>
      <summary>Did you test Mixture of Experts (MoE)?</summary>
      <div>
        Not in this study. MoE strictly affects the MLP layers, not the Attention mechanism. However, it is an open research question whether MoE routing probabilities correlate with the V/Q signatures of the attention heads in the preceding layer.
      </div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>If the V/Q Law is universal, can we hardcode it before training?</summary>
      <div>
        Theoretically, yes. If we initialize the early layers with massive Query matrices and the late layers with massive Value matrices, we might accelerate convergence. This is a highly promising avenue for future "Taxonomy-Informed Initialization" research.
      </div>
    </details>
  </InterviewQuestions>

  <Connections 
    links={[
      { title: "Next Chapter: Critical Questions", url: "/attentionheadgenome/academy/part8-reviewer-defense" }
    ]}
  />

